  "informal_statement": "For coordinate points A=(x1,y1), B=(x2,y2), C=(x3,y3) with a right angle at B (the vectors A-B and C-B have dot product zero), the squared distance from A to C equals the sum of the squared distances from A to B and from B to C (the Pythagorean theorem).",
  "informal_proof_idea": "Expand (A-C) = (A-B) - (C-B) and square: |A-C|^2 = |A-B|^2 + |C-B|^2 - 2*(A-B)·(C-B). The dot-product hypothesis makes the cross term vanish. A bare `ring` attempt fails first (see the paired negative example negative.geometry.pythagorean_bare_ring_no_hypothesis_failure.v1): the goal only holds given the hypothesis, and `ring` cannot use hypotheses. `nlinarith [h]` closes it directly.",
  "formal_statement_pp": "theorem pythagorean_right_angle (x1 y1 x2 y2 x3 y3 : ℝ) (h : (x1 - x2) * (x3 - x2) + (y1 - y2) * (y3 - y2) = 0) : (x1 - x3) ^ 2 + (y1 - y3) ^ 2 = ((x1 - x2) ^ 2 + (y1 - y2) ^ 2) + ((x2 - x3) ^ 2 + (y2 - y3) ^ 2)",
